    <folder name="Application Components" id="id-6034ce578c764cb88ac34fd18f5631f4">
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ApplicationComponent" name="3D Web Viewer" id="id-cdfe1b18223844c89926bb15f47ace56">
        <documentation>Must-haves:
- View the relevant area in 3D
- Zoom in from city to building level and vice versa
- Pan and orbit the scene
- Save and recall a bookmarked view

- Show characteristics / attributes of a particular roof (per roof attributes)

(line 6):

* Show calculated rooftop potential (color-coded rooftops, including 'golden combinations'). 
   Two or more combinations are shown 
   Every building can have a singular roof option or multiple options. Multiple options are called 'golden combinations'. 
   --> No UX design yet for showing multiple options for a roof

* Show underlying parameters (these are shown in the scenario panel).
   Scenario panel: weight with the rooftop coloring  is part of preparing a scenario. Analysis is on non-dynamic data. It's preconfigured. These parameters can be shown. 
   The objective is to show what parameters were used in the preperation of the scenario. One cannot change these parameters in the analysis.
   
   Example: show a zone, and then you like select that 50% should be green and 50% solar? Assumption: analysis is done on static prepared scenario's. 
   This option is in 'Prepare scenario'. 

   Example: setting a certain target: 

Practical: the 3Dtiles contain building attributes that are shown when clicked on a building.

Nice-to-haves:
- Show attributes (like flooding) in the map: show those buildings that  do have a flood risk:
Two functionalities: 
* abilty to add / show / hide layers - Implemented by selecting a Geo layer that's shown in the 3D view. 
* highlight buildings based on attributes
</documentation>
        <property key="Coloring schema" value="Decided outside of the viewer. The viewer adopts the choosen colors based on the attributes of the roof"/>
        <property/>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ApplicationComponent" name="Add Custom properties" id="id-858d835e73b4498eb7c5895687a442d2">
        <documentation>Arthur mentioned the ability to add you own values to attributes. This may be needed if the source data does not have the information. Eg: whether a roof allready has solar panels. 
The idea is that the LA delivers the data with id, attribute,value that is combined in the CityJSON dataset. 

@@Where is the data stored that serves as input for this component? 

Allow the user to make manual adjustments to the data (e.g. changing the status of a building from 'high potential for solar panels' to 'already used for solar panels').
>>> perhaps this should be part of the pre-processing.&quot; => part of 'Apply custom attributes'

@@Assumptation is that a LA can deliver a file describing the areas/building/roofs that should be blurred and/or hidden

[F10] Future roof use is nice-to-have. However one can add custom properties on buildings/roofs and filter on this in the Web UI.</documentation>
        <property key="Potential technology solution" value="Cesium Ion"/>
        <property key="Potential technology solution" value="Rotterdam 3D"/>
      </element>
