  <folder name="Motivation" id="id-01dcf4dc985841868b324e75a0fb76fe" type="motivation">
    <folder name="Principles" id="id-b0180c687bfc413597df097806804d65">
      <element xsi:type="archimate:Principle" name="Open Source by Default (EUPL, MIT, Apache 2.0)" id="id-85da2163d3cb4365a76fd59ac1f341b6">
        <documentation>Statement:
- Software within the architecture is open source and published under a permissive license that allows unrestricted use, modification, and redistribution

Implications:
- Closed source requires explicit architectural justification
- Licenses must be OSI-approved and permissive
- Legal review is part of the exception process

EUPL: European Union Public Licence (prefered). otherwise MIT, Apache 2.0</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:Principle" name="Browser-first, low-friction access" id="id-4540606e7cf64e9c9853c31293f194b0">
        <documentation>Principle
- The system for analysis must be usable through a standard web browser, with no local installation or specialist client software.

Rationale: Maximises accessibility for planners, workshops, and pilots; reduces operational and adoption barriers.

Derived from statements
- [A1] User Interface (browser-based CesiumJS app)
- [A3] Tiling (streamed 3D Tiles in browser)
- [A8] OGC APIs (optional, not required for MVP)
- [A14] Security &amp; Privacy (no users/auth in MVP) 

</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:Principle" name="One canonical data model with stable identifiers" id="id-397378a5d6ba423c9d8dd6afe3aab135">
        <documentation>Principle
- A single canonical data model and stable identifiers must be used to link geometry, attributes, tiles, and scenarios.

Rationale
- Prevents ambiguity, brittle joins, and versioning chaos; enables reproducibility and interoperability.

Derived from statements
- [A5] Canonical data model (CityJSON + Rooftop Passport)
- [A11] Identifier policy (MultiRoofs_ID everywhere)
- [A4] Data (BAG / canonical IDs as anchors)
- [A8] Domain APIs (attributes linked via IDs, not geometry)</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:Principle" name="Minimal MVP with controlled extensibility" id="id-0922a95cd3d74d728dd79b25c0a61574">
        <documentation>Principle
- The MVP must minimise scope and operational complexity while explicitly leaving room for future extensions.
Rationale
- Avoids overengineering, keeps costs down, and supports learning through pilots.
Derived from statements
- [A2] ETL / Ingestion (no upload UI, specialist-driven)
- [A12] Exports &amp; reporting (CSV/PDF only)
- [A14] Security &amp; Privacy (baseline protections only)
- [A16] Monitoring &amp; logging (basic, outside web app)
- [A17] 16 Build &amp; deploy (simple repos, basic CI)</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:Principle" name="Precompute complexity, keep interaction fast" id="id-0b968375ef50499983fcbf1dc6c20798">
        <documentation>Principle
- Computationally heavy processing must occur offline; runtime interaction must remain fast, predictable, and lightweight.
Rationale
- Ensures smooth workshops, deterministic results, and avoids costly real-time processing.
Derived from statements
- [A3] Tiling (pre-generated 3D Tiles)
- [A2] ETL / Ingestion (offline preprocessing, validation)
- [A9] Determines how base scores per roof (i.e. colors) are computed.
- [A10] Scenario / calculation (precomputed scores, fast reweighting)
- [A15] Testing &amp; conformance (validation before use)</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:Principle" name="Open standards by default, vendor services as optional accelerators" id="id-11366d44cf12415f9ad7344550ad1974">
        <documentation>Principle
- Open standards are the baseline; proprietary or hosted services may be used only where they clearly accelerate delivery without locking in.
Rationale
- Protects long-term interoperability and reuse while allowing pragmatic MVP choices.
Derived from statements
- [A3] Tiling (3D Tiles open standard, Cesium Ion optional)
- [A8] OGC APIs (standards-based, optional)
- [A5] Canonical data model (CityJSON LoD2.2, extensions)
- [A13] Metadata &amp; catalogue (ISO19115 / DCAT alignment)</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:Principle" name="Store data where we can govern it, move it, and protect it" id="id-ae19e6f9e46d4d8c906a89bb1c32b011">
        <documentation> @@should this be a principle?

Data sovereignty

Rationale (Why this matters)

This principle ensures that storage decisions are not driven primarily by convenience, vendor features, or cost, but by the ability to actually govern the data.

It emphasizes that true data sovereignty requires:
	•	Enforceable control: you must be able to technically and legally enforce who can access the data and under which conditions.
	•	Governance by design: policies for retention, classification, auditing, and sharing must be executable, not aspirational.
	•	Portability and exit readiness: data must remain movable without dependency traps, enabling strategic flexibility.
	•	Capability over paperwork: contracts are important, but sovereignty is only real if you can prove it operationally.

In short: the safest place for data is not where it is “allowed” to be stored, but where you can still steer it.</documentation>
      </element>
    </folder>
    <folder name="Requirements" id="id-75c31d97e1f44cd09f89e71ee1acdf81">
      <folder name="ChatGPT generated (V0.9)" id="id-7f0308fa55e7464baa4b40174efb09cb">
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="3D city viewer" id="id-cd6e946364554a32a7922db0d6911f5f">
          <documentation>View and navigate the 3D twin; pan/zoom/orbit; roof colouring.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="CityJSON dataset (LOD2.2)" id="id-315f8e343fc1488eb8c9a6061109e29f">
          <documentation>CityJSON dataset prepared (LOD2.2) with conformance checks.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="Configurable calculation parameters" id="id-d518b7747b504cf892fbe507b981e218">
          <documentation>Change inputs and parameters of the calculation engine/model.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="DCAT-AP metadata record" id="id-fbb9aef6898b4d74ab3c301359ac6fc9">
          <documentation>DCAT-style metadata record (coverage, cadence, licence, contact).</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="ETL to CityJSON" id="id-d0c77388b8424c1297978555360bfd70">
          <documentation>ETL to transform input data to CityJSON.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="Export Analysis result into CSV, PDF" id="id-3dff4c8f520f40339c0f6a343f5d1d0a">
          <documentation>A roof with it's characterics. The most important details to use in the potential usage. 
A rooftop passport is basically a standardized digital profile of a building’s roof — a single, shared source of truth that describes what a roof is, can do, and is allowed to do.

🏗️ Physical characteristics
	•	Roof type (flat, pitched)
	•	Surface area &amp; usable area
	•	Load-bearing capacity
	•	Orientation and slope
	•	Height and accessibility

🌞 Potential &amp; use cases
	•	Solar energy potential (PV, solar thermal)
	•	Green roof suitability (water retention, biodiversity)
	•	Blue roof potential (water buffering)
	•	Space for heat pumps or other installations

📜 Rules &amp; constraints
	•	Zoning and building regulations
	•	Heritage or monument restrictions
	•	Fire safety and access rules
	•	Ownership and split incentives (VvE / HOA)

📊 Operational context (optional)
	•	Current installations
	•	Maintenance status
	•	Links to energy use, climate goals, or subsidy schemes
</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="Exports (CSV/GeoJSON/report)" id="id-76d31caf0f0d4383bc9dd967844b8a26">
          <documentation>CSV/GeoJSON export; exportable scenario report with summary KPIs.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="Federated hybrid hosting" id="id-db81cd5399124da5b3e7ba2f10717410">
          <documentation>Central cloud for open info; local component for sensitive processing.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="Filtering and sorting" id="id-dd8c944a64f3484cb826016b6d813d17">
          <documentation>Filter/sort buildings by attributes (owner type, energy label, confidence score, etc.).</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="Layer toggling and comparison" id="id-f45c6cc95290472aba2d2134d9b86383">
          <documentation>Toggle hard and calculated layers; compare layers.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="Methodology transparency" id="id-8ebfd503693a448ab7bcf6c21863b8b2">
          <documentation>Information section explaining methodology; adjust parameters to local preferences.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="Modular monolith initially" id="id-147c6dc065324707b141f61ecdb863c3">
          <documentation>Start as modular monolith; split later if needed.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="MultiRoofs_ID generation" id="id-d27ad2a90ca14a6dafd6f6c7bd6658d0">
          <documentation>Generate IDs where authoritative IDs missing, incl. provenance + confidence.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="MVP open data only" id="id-0b4a4e4925b348de81d45b467d4f3305">
          <documentation>MVP uses publicly available non-sensitive data; sensitive data stays local if used.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="Per-roof inspection" id="id-14b2b5aed3dd47ffb8577e88c15467c2">
          <documentation>Inspect geometry and metrics per building/roof.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="Policy objective allocation" id="id-3c49b4b8dcdc453ea9428f4326cf4677">
          <documentation>Allocate city/municipal objectives to neighbourhood based on quick scan potential.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="Public read access (MVP)" id="id-bec40c106f524f7ba6264367e1e135cf">
          <documentation>Public-read access by default; note future OIDC/RBAC for protected datasets.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="Scenario comparison" id="id-125dd5af4d7c4c509be9261fc42da8fc">
          <documentation>Compare multiple scenarios with exports and maps.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="Scenario engine (MVP)" id="id-792602f141a54d39a1b01a552a20ba07">
          <documentation>Create one scenario, set simple weights, compute and visualise results.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="Sensitive buildings should not be visible to everyone" id="id-89e216e7b5dc42f49f79252fd97a30b3">
          <documentation>Perhaps the webviewer should not be open to everyone, so only authorized people. 
Not showing the buildings may lead to missing data conclusion (Sara)
Ali: guideline from government is required. Jan Henk: we cannot decide ourselves. 
Hiske: Technical feasible? Yes</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="The user can save and re-open a 3D scenario with the same settings (angle, zoom, area)" id="id-c70c3368868544ab94c1677e06006ba4">
          <documentation>angle, zoom, pan location, visible layers, parameters, filters</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="Users can self-serve" id="id-1ad9542463f74408b225ac634892c984">
          <documentation>Users should be able to use the tool by themselves (no facilitator required).</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="Validation (val3dity/CityJSON validator)" id="id-4fabb227674046fd99d9fe3b6b188cf6">
          <documentation>CityJSON conformance checks using validation tooling.</documentation>
        </element>
      </folder>
      <folder name="Decision Catalogue (V1.1)" id="id-6097c13a59674a13a47fc02e09d9fd7f">
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F1] User group - Use the tool insight in a rooftop redevelopment program" id="id-64d84a793b4b49bca71079e9006df72b">
          <documentation>Must have:
&quot;* Prioritize policymakers (urban planner, program manager);
* LA Technical expert (support role) will prepare scenarios.&quot;

Nice-to-have
&quot;Additional views for: 
* Home owners (housing corporations)
* Property/Building owners
* Architect (to be distinguished; inside or outside of LA?)&quot;</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F2] Viewing &amp; navigation - See and navigate the 3D city context" id="id-5223e26fa3964ca6ba2dd89280903697">
          <documentation>Must-have:
View the relevant area in 3D
</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F3] Viewing &amp; navigation - Move smoothly across scales" id="id-f12bd574ddd84f93ba9078cb0269e731">
          <documentation>Must have: 
Zoom in from city to building level and vice versa
</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F4] Viewing &amp; navigation - Re‑orient the scene" id="id-637e278e634647ce884161b2f21d2073">
          <documentation>Must have: 
Pan and orbit the scene

Nice-to-hace:
Reset view to selected area or full extent</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F5] Layers &amp; visualization - Show raw input data (layer)" id="id-a42e93acd6f441daa88d2ab43de563b6">
          <documentation>Must have:
* Input data is viewed in roof/building record (not as a layer).

Nice-to-have:
&quot;>>> If available:
* Show land use/zoning maps;
* Show flood risk maps;
* Show heat island maps;
* Show other maps (green/parks, socio-economic metrics, etc.)&quot;</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F6] Layers &amp; visualization - Show computed insights" id="id-8547dcb7455f41869c5c81df33e210be">
          <documentation>Must have:
&quot;* Show calculated rooftop potential (color-coded rooftops, including 'golden combinations' - i.e. two or more functions);
* Show underlying parameters (these are shown in the scenario panel).&quot;

Nice-to-have:
&quot;* Show constraints (e.g. max. number of stories because of Omgevingswet constraints);
* Show sub-categories of color-coded roofs (e.g. several types of green roofs).&quot;</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F7] Inspection - See summary dataset per city/area" id="id-009c735c264c496c9e258ffa78c9a2b0">
          <documentation>Must have:
* Show (aggregated) information (e.g. # roofs) and potential (e.g. #m2 potential for yellow roofs).</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F8] Inspection - Open a roof/building record" id="id-391b706954a7457fb4110ccea9a9337a">
          <documentation>Must have:
Click a roof to view its details (e.g. See area (m²), slope (°), elevation (m).)

Nice-to-have:
* View additional metrics (if available);</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F9] Inspection - See current use of rooftops" id="id-5557426d08694c0ebfe5ebdbb4297401">
          <documentation>Must have:
&quot;>>> If data is available;
* View existing roof use (rooftop color-coded schema);
* Warning message should appear of conflicting rooftop usage.&quot;</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F10] Inspection - See future use of rooftops" id="id-568125bab4044476900a7dde7ad07d89">
          <documentation>Nice-to-have:
Show planned roof use and/or reconstruction.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F11] Inspection - Check constraints" id="id-e021e643ea914215995f34f9e678dfa3">
          <documentation>Must have:
&quot;>>> See ID9
>>> If data is available and methodology is feasible:
* Show heritage, zoning, flood/heat/noise, grid and other constraints (e.g. as flags/filter or warning message).&quot;</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F12] Inspection - See data recency" id="id-1df363638ad440f9baf1ab869ea7e8a7">
          <documentation>Must have:
See when data was last updated.</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F13] Inspection - Filter relevant roofs " id="id-a855ca6c743142bbb9340d6a884ed178">
          <documentation>Must have:
&quot;Filter by:
* Potential (e.g. more than >x m2 of green roof), i.e. value and range;
* Owner type (e.g., private, housing corp, public);
* Feasibility threshold;
* Other attributes.&quot;

Nice-to-have:
Save and name a filter for later reuse</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F14] Upload - Update data manually" id="id-e9c61537952e4f7db0928060fddb5426">
          <documentation>Nice-to-have:
&quot;Allow the user to make manual adjustments to the data (e.g. changing the status of a building from 'high potential for solar panels' to 'already used for solar panels').
>>> perhaps this should be part of the pre-processing.&quot;</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F15] Scenario analysis - Prepare scenario (pre-workshop)" id="id-52796a7cadba432db08beeaf946d67c6">
          <documentation>&quot;In preparation of an interactive session with end-users, the technical expert should be able to:
* Configure the scenario engine; 
* Prepare supporting data; 
* Prepare several scenarios;
* Save scenarios for reuse.&quot;</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F16] Scenario analysis - Create scenario (during workshop)" id="id-344f1b6c9dbc4f8e9eae706692072ad4">
          <documentation>Must have:
&quot;During an interactive session with end-users, the end-user should be able to:
* Toggle scenario panel on/off;
* Adjust model weights to reflect priorities and constraints for zones/ functions;
* Change feasibility thresholds for selected functions;
* Draw activation zones on the map;
* Set simple policy targets (e.g., minimal m2 of green roof);
* Save the calculated scenario and input parameters.&quot;

Nice-to-have:
* More complex client-side scenario modelling (heavier impact on backend).</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F17] Scenario analysis - Allocate policy ambitions to areas" id="id-d487e9994be74f6d99b5b3a04dfbf576">
          <documentation>Nice-to-have:
Auto‑allocate city targets to neighbourhoods (quick scan)</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F18] Scenario analysis - Upload local datasets" id="id-a1e59a0e429249d2a5961c700798d4bd">
          <documentation>Nice-to-have:
&quot;>>> If possible;
* Upload additional map layers for local analysis&quot;</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F19] Scenario analysis - Compare scenarios" id="id-295c71d08a244bed91d64daaf54e13a2">
          <documentation>Nice-to-have:
&quot;* Compare current scenario to baseline (map + table);
* Compare multiple saved scenarios side‑by‑side&quot;</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F20] Scenario analysis - Rank opportunities" id="id-d7548bcd43534e6fb711e075ed6d4198">
          <documentation>Must have:
View top‑ranked areas/roofs/buildings per function</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F21] Scenario analysis - Summarise results" id="id-41dfc63e03b54355a25a8cece514de84">
          <documentation>Must have:
View city/area/building‑level summary (m² by use, kWh, m³ retention, counts)</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F22] Exports &amp; reporting - Export data in CSV" id="id-9f61229d84f240b9b72a61cbeb4b4853">
          <documentation>Must have:
&quot;* Export calculation engine input data (CSV);
* Export selected roofs and building output dataset (CSV)&quot;</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F23] Exports &amp; reporting - Additional export options" id="id-82e38a5fae45451abd7c09441943872b">
          <documentation>Nice-to-have:
&quot;* Export as .ai, .pdf, .eps;
* Generate an export image and AI-generated image of rooftop;
* Generate a scenario report (PDF) with maps and summary KPIs;
* Generate a scenario comparison (PDF) with deltas.&quot;</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F24] Help &amp; methodology - Trust the methodolgy" id="id-5146ecf6d9f541a58944d9096c06020d">
          <documentation>Must have:
View a concise methodology page

Nice-to-have:
Contextual tooltips explaining key fields</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="[F25] Help &amp; methodology - Get started quickly" id="id-dc5d6d0acd40439db2dcdac388cc28c5">
          <documentation>Must have:
View a quick‑start guide

Nice-to-have:
Link to a fuller method note/library</documentation>
        </element>
      </folder>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:Requirement" name="Make dataset Findable (metadata)" id="id-391cec28254d49629532c301c899df8b">
        <documentation>For geospatial: ISO19115 compliant metadata fields. @@Scope - what fields? How about publishing @@. So - OASC needs to check conformance. 

DCAT - Dataportal? Not needed. Not part of the scope. </documentation>
      </element>
    </folder>
    <folder name="Goals" id="id-45653439c787481583fb919a878cf400">
      <element xsi:type="archimate:Goal" name="Enable rooftop utilisation decision support" id="id-cf3839c9a7774c9ba2508e9141956a28">
        <documentation>Provide a tool to explore rooftop potential and support decisions.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:Goal" name="Enable scenario-based exploration" id="id-b7b28b8c19ee4b01b24ab2942a666b22">
        <documentation>Allow creation, comparison and export of rooftop utilisation scenarios.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:Goal" name="Reusable reference solution for Local Authorities" id="id-affd97544161460f8ac1c4a4103eac78">
        <documentation>Standardised reference solution with per-LA configuration.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:Outcome" name="Shared understanding of rooftop potential" id="id-c1c6bc6ac9ce4dc68faf8466cc62a1cd">
        <documentation>Stakeholders align on opportunities/constraints via common visualisations and metrics.</documentation>
      </element>
    </folder>
    <folder name="Drivers" id="id-fd0624525ba84ab4a7fb74f771ea1f9e">
      <element xsi:type="archimate:Driver" name="Need for cross-stakeholder dialogue" id="id-0a431cbe23044e0eaec24bf5ab77599e">
        <documentation>Facilitate discussion between experts/parties involved in urban planning and development.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:Driver" name="Need for evidence-based urban planning" id="id-2db646cb54b34368bd79b37befe099e9">
        <documentation>Support policy and planning with quantitative and spatial insight.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:Driver" name="Need for interoperability and standards" id="id-2b3ccaf7a73045e7a83f99c7cc195596">
        <documentation>Conform to CityJSON, DCAT-AP, MIM7 and (future) OGC APIs.</documentation>
      </element>
    </folder>
    <folder name="Constraints" id="id-0dc44811a65c4dd9a16e2f24877c3b80">
      <element xsi:type="archimate:Constraint" name="Data Usage licences" id="id-8f13d1870826493b8cb3ad1eafbd0d69">
        <documentation>Data usage licenses - CC0 Commons (eg: https://data.overheid.nl/ondersteuning/data-publiceren/licentie-keuze)
A license constraint can be related to a specific datasource (type). Eg. BAG Data is open data with a CC0 license. </documentation>
      </element>
    </folder>
  </folder>
  <folder name="Implementation &amp; Migration" id="id-9a0e74dc726f4af390dcbaabff00d88b" type="implementation_migration">
    <folder name="Implementation" id="id-7b70bf52dbff46caae365d934caab283">
